    <section class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed space-y-6">
      <p>Many Malaysian SMEs treat packing as an afterthought — a task done at a spare corner of the warehouse, often by whoever is free. The result is slow throughput, inconsistent packaging quality, and preventable damage claims. A properly designed packing station, stocked with the right materials and organised for workflow efficiency, can transform this situation — often doubling output per worker-hour.</p>

      <p>Quinocycle Sdn. Bhd. has supplied warehouse packaging materials to businesses across Balakong, Cheras, Kajang, and greater Selangor for over 15 years. Here is our practical guide to setting up a packing station that actually works.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">The Anatomy of a High-Efficiency Packing Station</h2>
      <p>An efficient packing station reduces the number of steps, reaches, and decisions a packer must make per order. Every tool and material has a designated place within arm's reach. The layout follows a logical flow: incoming orders → packing bench → seal & label → dispatch area.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">The Packing Bench</h3>
      <p>The foundation of every station is a sturdy work surface at elbow height (typically 85–95cm for a standing worker). A wooden or steel bench of at least 120cm × 80cm gives you enough room to work a large box without items falling off the edges. Install a lower shelf beneath the bench to store frequently used box sizes — immediately accessible without walking away from the station.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Vertical Storage for Consumables</h3>
      <p>Mount a vertical rack or pegboard behind the packing bench for roll holders, tape dispensers, scissors, and labels. Keeping these items at eye or shoulder level means packers never lose momentum searching for supplies. Dedicate hooks for bubble wrap rolls, stretch film rolls, and kraft paper — the three most commonly grabbed materials mid-pack.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Essential Supplies Checklist for a Malaysian Warehouse Packing Station</h2>

      <div class="bg-surface-variant/50 border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-2xl p-6 my-8">
        <h3 class="font-headline text-lg font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Packing Station Supplies Checklist</h3>
        <div class="space-y-2 font-body text-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">Carton boxes — at least 3 sizes (S, M, L) for your most common product ranges</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">OPP tape rolls + gun dispenser (2–3 per station to avoid downtime during roll change)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">Bubble wrap roll (small and large bubble) on mounted dispenser</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">Corrugated sheet stack for layer pads and fillers</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">Weighing scale (to verify shipment weight for courier pricing)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">Label printer + labels (A6 thermal labels for courier waybills)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1 border-b border-outline-variant/20">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">Box cutter / stanley knife (replaced blade monthly)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 py-1">
            <span class="text-primary font-bold">✓</span>
            <span class="text-on-surface">Marker for manual labelling if needed</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Workflow Layout: The One-Way Flow Principle</h2>
      <p>The most efficient packing stations are designed so goods flow in one direction — never backward. Products arrive from the pick zone on the left, are packed at the centre bench, then move right to the seal-and-label area, then forward to the dispatch staging zone. This prevents the confusion and cross-movement that slows teams down in busy warehouse environments.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Colour Coding and Visual Management</h3>
      <p>For warehouses running multiple product lines, colour-coded tape or labels for different destinations or product categories reduces errors significantly. Use coloured stickers or coloured tape to mark "urgent," "fragile," and "standard" packs at a glance. This simple visual system allows supervisors to spot priority orders quickly across a busy packing floor.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Stocking Your Station: Wholesale Supplies from Quinocycle</h2>
